## Memory Safety

### Ownership and Borrowing

Rust's ownership system prevents memory safety bugs at compile time. Follow these
patterns:

```rust
// GOOD: Clear ownership transfer
fn process_data(data: Vec<u8>) -> Result<(), Error> {
    // data is owned here, will be dropped at end of scope
    validate(&data)?;
    Ok(())
}

// GOOD: Borrowing for read-only access
fn validate(data: &[u8]) -> Result<(), Error> {
    if data.is_empty() {
        return Err(Error::EmptyInput);
    }
    Ok(())
}

// AVOID: Unnecessary cloning
fn bad_pattern(data: &Vec<u8>) {
    let owned = data.clone(); // Unnecessary allocation
    process(owned);
}
```

### Sensitive Data Handling

Use the `zeroize` crate to securely clear sensitive data:

```rust
use zeroize::{Zeroize, ZeroizeOnDrop};

#[derive(Zeroize, ZeroizeOnDrop)]
struct SecretKey {
    bytes: [u8; 32],
}

// Data is automatically zeroed when dropped
fn use_key() {
    let key = SecretKey { bytes: [0u8; 32] };
    // ... use key ...
} // key.bytes zeroed here

// For temporary secrets
fn process_password(password: &str) {
    let mut password_bytes = password.as_bytes().to_vec();
    // ... use password_bytes ...
    password_bytes.zeroize(); // Explicit zeroing
}
```

### Preventing Buffer Overflows

```rust
// GOOD: Use checked indexing
fn safe_access(data: &[u8], index: usize) -> Option<u8> {
    data.get(index).copied()
}

// GOOD: Use iterators instead of manual indexing
fn process_all(data: &[u8]) {
    for byte in data {
        process_byte(*byte);
    }
}

// AVOID: Unchecked indexing
fn unsafe_access(data: &[u8], index: usize) -> u8 {
    data[index] // Can panic!
}
```

